<p>Anki has been the dominant spaced repetition flashcard application for over a decade, and it remains a powerful tool for dedicated learners. However, its interface has changed little since its creation, and new users often find the setup process overwhelming. FluentCards was designed specifically to address these pain points while maintaining the core spaced repetition functionality that makes Anki effective.</p>

<h2>Setup Time Comparison</h2>
<p>Setting up Anki requires downloading the desktop application, creating an AnkiWeb account for sync, configuring add-ons for features like TTS and furigana, and learning the card creation syntax. This process can take over an hour for a new user. FluentCards requires no setup whatsoever. Open the app and start studying immediately. Starter decks are pre-loaded, TTS is built in, and furigana works automatically. The difference in time from deciding to study to actually studying is dramatic.</p>

<h2>Mobile Experience</h2>
<p>Anki's mobile experience is fragmented. The desktop application is free, but the official iOS app costs $24.99. The free Android app is community-maintained and lags behind the desktop version. Syncing between devices requires an AnkiWeb account and can be unreliable. FluentCards works on any device with a browser, including iOS and Android, with no app installation required. The experience is identical on all platforms, and syncing is seamless with Google sign-in.</p>

<h2>Modern Features Out of the Box</h2>
<p>Anki requires add-ons for features that FluentCards includes by default. TTS pronunciation needs the "AwesomeTTS" add-on, which requires configuration for each language. Furigana for Japanese requires the "Ajatt-Tools" add-on. Automatic mnemonic image generation is not available in Anki at all. FluentCards includes all of these features built in, working immediately with no configuration required. The AI mnemonic generator and furigana rendering are exclusive to FluentCards.</p>

<h2>User Interface and Design</h2>
<p>Anki's interface, while functional, has a steep learning curve. The card browser, deck options, and add-on manager each have their own complex interface paradigms. FluentCards uses a modern, intuitive interface designed for first-time users. The study screen is minimal and focused, the deck management is straightforward, and all settings are accessible from a clean navigation bar. For users who prioritize ease of use alongside powerful functionality, FluentCards offers the best balance.</p>


<h2>Who Should Choose FluentCards</h2>
<p>FluentCards is ideal for new language learners who want to start immediately without complex setup. It is also excellent for experienced learners who want modern features like built-in TTS, automatic furigana, and AI mnemonics without installing add-ons. The app works equally well for casual learners who study a few minutes per day and serious learners with thousands of cards.</p>
<h2>Making the Switch from Anki</h2>
<p>If you are currently using Anki, you can export your decks to CSV and import them into FluentCards. The app supports bulk card creation, making it easy to transfer large decks. Once imported, your cards benefit from FSRS-5, TTS, and all other FluentCards features. You can maintain both apps during the transition and gradually shift to FluentCards.</p>


<h2>Cost Comparison</h2>
<p>Anki is free on desktop and Android, but the official iOS application costs $24.99. The mobile app is essential for studying on the go, which means iOS users must pay to access the full Anki experience. Additionally, AnkiWeb sync is free but has storage limitations. FluentCards is completely free on all platforms with no paid apps, no subscriptions, and no feature limitations. The same full-featured experience is available on desktop, iOS, Android, and any device with a modern web browser. For users who want a powerful flashcard system without the scattered costs and platform limitations, FluentCards provides a unified free solution.</p>
<h2>Updates and Development</h2>
<p>Anki receives regular updates from its primary developer and community contributors, but major new features are relatively infrequent. The Anki codebase is mature and changes slowly. FluentCards is actively developed with new features, improvements, and optimizations being added regularly. Recent additions include FSRS-5 support, AI-powered mnemonic images, in-app browser detection for Google sign-in, guided tours for new users, and a redesigned study interface. The active development pace means FluentCards users benefit from continuous improvements without needing to manage add-ons or extensions.</p>

